('1005856', 'Gisa Vadhika Sacawisastra', 'Ideology in Pramoedya Ananta Toer''s Footsteps', 'Bahasa dan Sastra Inggris', 'FAKULTAS PENDIDIKAN BAHASA DAN SASTRA', 'Dr. Rd. Safrina, M.A.', '', '	This study is conducted to construct ideology in Pramoedya Ananta Toer''s Footsteps. In order to construct ideology in the novel, Eagleton''s theory of six ideological features is employed as the tool to analyze the text. This study finds that there are two dominant class ideologies which are constructed in the novel, which are capitalism and feudalism. This study also finds that the characters are attributed with five ideological features, which are legitimation, rationalization, action-oriented, universalization, and naturalization to maintain the domination and advantages of the dominant classes and their ideologies.\r\nKeywords: ideology, unifying, action-oriented, rationalization, legitimation, naturalization, universalization\r\nSupervisor: Dr. Rd. Safrina Noorman, M.A.\r\n	Penelitian ini dilakukan untuk mengkonstruksi ideologi dalam novel Footsteps karangan Pramoedya Ananta Toer. Untuk mengkons...'),
('1005876', 'Imam', 'Alienation In Murakami''s Blind Willow Sleeping Woman', 'Bahasa dan Sastra Inggris', 'FAKULTAS PENDIDIKAN BAHASA DAN SASTRA', 'Dr. Rd. Safrina, M.A.', '', 'This study explores the aspects of alienation in three selected short stories from Blind Willow, Sleeping Woman: "A Folklore for My Generation: A Pre-History of Late-Stage Capitalism," "Tony Takitani," and "Firefly," and how these aspects manifest in the lives of the people in the selected stories. The study was conducted under postmodernist approach and employs Seeman''s Alienation Aspects (1959) as the theoretical framework of the study. The findings divulge that there are four alienation aspects palpable in the selected short stories: powerlessness, meaninglessness, normlessness, and social isolation. The alienation aspects found manifest through four key points i.e. the unknown origins of alienation, the problem of choices overload, the fragmentation of life aspects, and disconnected relational self. In postmodern perspective, Murakami''s Blind Willow, Sleeping Woman can be interpreted as a r...'),
